## Real-World Pentest Application

During internal network assessments, services are frequently running on non-standard ports. An attacker who only checks the top 1000 ports or only looks for HTTP/HTTPS will miss them. This level forces the habit of scanning full port ranges and fingerprinting what you find rather than assuming what's there.

The SSL identification workflow here — scan, connect with `openssl s_client`, look for a completed handshake — is directly applicable to any engagement where you're probing internal services that may be encrypted. Knowing how to interact manually with SSL-wrapped services without a browser or proxy is a foundational skill.

The RSA key delivery is also a realistic scenario. Not all credential material is a plaintext password. Knowing how to handle, store and use an RSA private key on the fly is something you'll do repeatedly in real engagements.
